)\n\nThe **cannot_move_when_borrowed** method (line 16) creates an error using the session_diagnostics::MoveBorrow struct, which is tagged with code E0505.\n\n### 5. Session Diagnostics (`compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/session_diagnostics.rs`)\n\nThe **MoveBorrow** struct (line 286) is decorated with #[diag(borrowck_cannot_move_when_borrowed, code = E0505)], establishing the error code and message template.\n\n### 6. Error Code Definition (`compiler/rustc_error_codes/src/error_codes/E0505.md`)\n\nDefines the human-readable explanation and examples for E0505, including the error message template: \"A value was moved out while it was still borrowed.\"\n\n## Summary of the Detection Chain:\n\n1. MIR visitor processes statements/terminators\n2. Operand::Move detection triggers consume_operand\n3. access_place called with WriteKind::Move\n4. check_access_for_conflict detects conflict with active borrows\n5. report_move_out_while_borrowed called to format error\n6. cannot_move_when_borrowed creates E0505 diagnostic\n7. MoveBorrow struct renders the final error message\n\nThis design separates concerns: the borrow checker core identifies violations, conflict detection determines error types, and diagnostics handle formatting and user-facing messages."
